<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900507-0037</DOCNO><DOCID>900507-0037.</DOCID><HL>   Woolworth April Sales   Increased 21%, Boosted   By Easter Shopping</HL><DATE>05/07/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2</SO><CO>   Z</CO><IN>BROADLINE RETAILERS, DEPARTMENT STORES (RTB)</IN><LP>   NEW YORK -- Woolworth Corp.'s April sales soared 21%,because the period included Easter buying while theyear-earlier period didn't.   Domestic sales rose to $421 million in the four weeksended April 28, compared with $348 million a year earlier.Equally impressive, domestic sales growth for stores open atleast one year increased 18%.</LP><TEXT>   &quot;Our April sales were unusually positive because we hadall of the Easter business, as opposed to last year, whenEaster occurred in March,&quot; said Harold Sells, chairman andchief executive of the retailer. If March and April weretaken as a single reporting period, he said, domestic saleswere up 8.3% and domestic comparable store sales rose 5.4%.   Mr. Sells said that Woolworth was particularly strong inEaster candies and gifts, as well as merchandise related tothe Simpsons, which are popular TV cartoon characters. Ninjaturtles and Nintendo game cartridges were also in demand,said Mr. Sells. The apparel business was mixed. Men's apparelwas strong, but children's apparel sales softened.   &quot;About half of our Kids Mart children's stores are inCaifornia, and last year they had an unusual heat wave thatbenefited us tremendously,&quot; said Mr. Sells. &quot;This year theweather was back to normal. We showed gains, but not as muchas in men's wear.&quot;   For the 13 weeks ended April 28, domestic sales increased9.7% to $1.23 billion against $1.12 billion in 1989.</TEXT></DOC>